episodes.title: Lawyer: Partial Epstein files disclosure fuels speculation that DOJ 'is trying to protect somebody'
episodes.description:
The US Justice Department has released a trove of documents related to the prosecution of convicted sex offender Jeffrey Epstein. US Representatives Ro Khanna (Democrat) and Thomas Massie (Republican) have been pressing for the release of the documents in accordance with the "Epstein Files Transparency Act," and say the recent release does not comply with the law. The release leaves out many documents in the DOJ's possession and is criticized by both Democratic and Republican lawmakers for redacting potentially valuable information. 

Chapter Breakdown
00:00 Lawmakers criticize DOJ's redacted release of Epstein files
0:28 Ethan Bearman, Attorney and Adjunct Professor at Loyola Law School, LA, as to why the DOJ release is not in compliance with the law
4:34 What's been redacted in the Epstein files?

episodes.title: Can the Epstein files release calm Trump's MAGA backlash? | DW News | DW News
episodes.description:
The documents released on Friday are roughly 4,000 images in five data sets. That is a thin slice of the hundreds of thousands of files the Department of Justice has. In a letter to Congress obtained by Associated Press, the Department of Justice acknowledged that the complete set of files was not released and that the government expects more disclosures by the end of the year. Of the documents that were released, many were heavily redacted without explanation. For instance, over 100 images were entirely blacked out, without explanations. Dozens of other images showed staircases. It is unclear how substantive the data sets are given the lack of context from the Department of Justice.

episodes.title: (Former) Prince Andrew's fall from grace: Could royal now face police enquiries? | DW News
episodes.description:
The name Andrew Albert Christian Edward Mountbatten Windsor might sound regal, but it's missing one word - "Prince". Britain's King Charles has begun the process of removing his brother Andrew's royal titles. The former prince has also been told to vacate his royal residence. For months, pressure to act has been mounting on the King over Andrew's links to the late convicted sex offender Jeffrey Epstein. 

The family of the late Virginia Giuffre, who accused Andrew of sexual abuse, welcomed the decision. They are now calling for an investigation into the former prince, though Andrew has always denied any wrongdoing.
